l exerciseCached. There's also the issue of Checkstyle’s \\\"Cyclomatic complexity,\\\" and I think this repo might have it. There's a potential bug related to the NativeImageSupport import. If isolatedLocation isn't null and the patched dynamic class loading throws an UnsupportedFeatureError, we catch it, but that could affect the original path, which might use restricted access methods. I'm weighing the risks of executing exerciseCached in the native context.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Analyzing reflection and metadata issues**\\n\\nI’m considering that adding reflection to a private method may require metadata generated by the agent. If they run natively after that, the test using reflection should generate the metadata on the JVM. The native image configuration includes test resources without modifications, which could complicate things. I’m thinking about removing the original exerciseCached to minimize risk. The patched loader runs only under isolated paths on the JVM, and I want to ensure native tests pass without causing any issues. Should I remove the exerciseCachedDirectBufferConstructor entirely?\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Refining patch details**\\n\\nThe patched class sets the constructor in clinit and invokes allocateDirectNoCleaner, which covers line 181. The original exerciseCached was just a previous attempt, and if the patched version fails, the test fails as well. I’m thinking about removing the function/StaticFieldRestorer/Constructor import for clarity, which will streamline the patch a bit. In the isolated branch, I'll only call exercisePatched and not use exerciseCached after the original path. It seems constructor imports in the patched section aren't necessary, which is good. However, if findIsolatedLibraryLocation is null on JVM coverage, the patched version won't run.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_n2wnhy7YwEVimr7H1yvnjRKx|fc_0cc1e82129ed72300169fdf1c011d48191a1a47c680a92554f", "name": "edit", "arg